The Pronunciation of the Word “Māori”

30/08/2023

1 Overview

This document presents the analysis steps and results for ‘The Pronunciation of the Word “Māori”’.

The following sections cover:

  1. loading data and libraries,
  2. initial data examination,
  3. the binary flap model,
  4. the binary diphthong model, and
  5. the diphthong ratio model.

NB: we are not able to share the data for this project due to research ethics commitments. We provide this markdown to indicate the data processing steps which we have carried out and to provide.

2 Load data and libraries

We load the required libraries.

# Tidyverse contains plotting and data manipulation functions used throughout
# this markdown file.
library(tidyverse)
library(gt) # gt provides additional table output options.

# Linear mixed modelling
library(lme4)
library(effects)
library(emmeans)

We read in the data and create a binary variable indicating whether a token is a diphthong or not. All diphthong tokens have a ‘ratio’ of /a:/ to /o/, so we can create a binary variable by indicating ‘not diphthong’ for every token without a ratio.

merged_data <- read_rds('merged_data.rds')

merged_data <- merged_data |> 
  # Store flap info as a factor for modelling.
  mutate(
    Flap = as.factor(Flap),
    generation = factor(
      merged_data$generation, levels=c("Hist", "TK", "Pres", "L1", "L2")
    ),
    Ratio = as.numeric(str_replace_all(Ratio, ",", "\\."))
  )

filtered_data <- merged_data |>
  # Remove Tūhoe speakers (for models with gender)
  filter(
    !generation == "TK"
  ) |> 
  # create diphthong variable. Ngāi Tūhoe speakers were not included in the 
  # diphthong models as gender was found to be significant.
  mutate(
    diphthong = as.factor(if_else(is.na(Ratio), 'n', 'y'))
  )

4 Flap model

4.1 Without Tūhoe speakers

For all models, we start with a maximal structure with three way interactions for language, gender, and generation, along with random intercepts and slopes on language for each speaker. If none of the coefficients for a predictor are significant at the 0.05 level, we remove the predictor from subsequent models.

The following code fits the first model.

Flapmodel0 <- glmer(
  # Dependent variable
  Flap ~ 
    # Independent variables / Main effects / predictors
    generation * participant_gender * participant_language + 
    # Random effects
    (1 + participant_language|CleanSpeaker), 
  # Family binomial because it's a 'yes or no' modelling problem.
  family = "binomial", 
  # Tell it the dataset.
  data = filtered_data, 
  # Some magic words to give the model additional time to 'converge'.
  glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 1e7)),
  # Optimizer chosen using 'allFit' function
)

Let’s have a look at this model. First the summary.

The following description was written from one author to another. We leave it in in case it is useful for any readers.

These values are a bit inscrutable by themselves. We will plot some effects in a moment to help understand them. But some general patterns are clear. The first thing to look at is the (Intercept) value. This is the estimate for the base level of the generation variable (i.e., Hist).

The historical female speakers have a statistically significant (see the star) estimate of -2.32. ‘Significance’ here means that the model is confident that the true value is not 0. The fact that the estimate is lower than 0 (i.e., is negative), means the model estimates female historical speakers, speaking English, to have a lower than 50/50 chance of flapping.

The other values in the summary are interpreted with respect to the base level. We add or subtract the values to the base level. e.g. to get the estimate for historical male speakers speaking English, we add the value for participant_genderM (0.21409) to the coefficient above (-2.32) to get (-2.10591) this value is still negative, so the model still takes male historical speakers to have a lower than 50/50 chance of flapping while speaking English. But note, the value for participant_genderM is not statistically significant (there’s no star in the relevant row of the table). So the model is not confident that there is in reality any difference in the proportion of flapping between the genders in the historical speakers.

Before visualising, we continue to backfit. Note that none of the three way interactions terms in the summary above are statistically significant. We fit a new model without three way interactions.

Flapmodel1 <- glmer(
  # Dependent variable
  Flap ~ 
    # Independent variables / Main effects
    generation + participant_language + participant_gender +  
    generation : participant_language +
    generation : participant_gender +
    participant_language : participant_gender + 
    # Random effects
    (1 + participant_language|CleanSpeaker), 
  # Family binomial because it's a 'yes or no' modelling problem.
  family = "binomial", 
  # Tell it the dataset.
  data = filtered_data, 
  # Some magic words to give the model additional time to 'congerge'.
  glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 1e7))
)

We now turn to plotting model estimates.

mod_effects <- effect(
  term='generation:participant_language',
  mod=Flapmodel2
)

to_plot <- as_tibble(mod_effects)

to_plot |> 
  ggplot(
    aes(
      x = generation,
      y = fit, 
      colour = participant_language
    )
  ) +
  # add points
  # 'position_dodge' separates the two languages on the plot.
  # If you increase the width, the points get further apart.
  # If you change the value, change it in the code for the error bars
  # below as well.
  geom_point(position = position_dodge(width=0.5)) +
  # add errorbars
  geom_errorbar(
    aes(
      ymin = lower, 
      ymax = upper
    ),
    position = position_dodge(width=0.5),
    width = 0.4 # width of error bars.
  ) +
  labs(
    y = "Proportion of flapped /r/ (predicted)",
    x = "Generation",
    colour = "Language"
  ) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_colour_grey(start = 0.6, end = 0)

Figure 4.1: Predicted flap proportions with 95% confidence intervals.

Figure 4.1 provides a much clearer indication of what is going on in this model. There is a large difference in flap proportion when speaking English and when speaking Māori. This difference seems reduced in the present day kaumātua, and is not present at all in the contemporary L1 and L2 speakers.

We generate p-values for these contrasts using the emmeans package.

model.emm <- emmeans(Flapmodel2, specs = ~ generation * participant_language)
contrast(model.emm, "pairwise", simple = "participant_language")
## generation = Hist:
##  contrast        estimate    SE  df z.ratio p.value
##  English - Maori  -2.8346 0.680 Inf  -4.166  <.0001
## 
## generation = Pres:

##  English - Maori  -0.9138 0.365 Inf  -2.506  0.0122
## 
## generation = L1:
##  contrast        estimate    SE  df z.ratio p.value
##  English - Maori  -0.3960 0.465 Inf  -0.851  0.3947

## generation = L2:
##  contrast        estimate    SE  df z.ratio p.value
##  English - Maori  -0.0901 0.496 Inf  -0.182  0.8558

## Results are given on the log odds ratio (not the response) scale.

These p-values match our visual judgement, where the historical and present day generations have p-values less than 0.05 for the contrast between English and Māori.

As a final check, to ensure we have the right model, we use the anova function.

anova(Flapmodel0, Flapmodel1, Flapmodel2)

The results above indicate that our final model is the best of the models considered.

4.2 With Tūhoe speakers

Since gender is not significant, we add the Tūhoe data back into the model.

Flapmodel2Tūhoe <- glmer(
  # Dependent variable
  Flap ~ 
    # Independent variables / Main effects
    generation * participant_language +
    # Random effects
    (1 + participant_language|CleanSpeaker), 
  # Family binomial because it's a 'yes or no' modelling problem.
  family = "binomial", 
  # Tell it the dataset.
  data = merged_data, 
  # Some magic words to give the model additional time to 'congerge'.
  glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 1e7))
)

5 Binary diphthong analysis

We now apply the same approach to the binary diphthong variable.

Dmodel0 <- glmer(
  # Dependent variable
  diphthong ~ 
    # Independent variables / Main effects
    generation * participant_gender * participant_language + 
    # Random effects
    (1 + participant_language|CleanSpeaker), 
  # Family binomial because it's a 'yes or no' modelling problem.
  family = "binomial", 
  # Tell it the dataset.
  data = filtered_data, 
  # Some magic words to give the model additional time to 'converge'.
  glmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 1e7)),
  # Optimizer chosen using 'AllFit' - most don't fit as we're at the limits of 
  # what we can fit with these data.
)

6 Diphthong ratio model

We now backfit using the diphthong ratio variable. This time we use a linear model, as the data is continuous.

Rmodel0 <- lmer(
  # Dependent variable
  Ratio ~ 
    # Independent variables / Main effects
    generation * participant_gender * participant_language + 
    # Random effects
    (1 + participant_language|CleanSpeaker), 
  # Tell it the dataset.
  data = filtered_data, 
  # Some magic words to give the model additional time to 'converge'.
  ## lmerControl(optimizer = "nlminbwrap", optCtrl = list(maxfun = 1e7)),
  # Optimizer chosen using 'AllFit' - most don't fit as we're at the limits of 
  # what we can fit with these data.
)

These linear models do not give p-values. We use t-values great than 2 as a rough heuristic for keeping terms in our model. In this case, each term has at least one ‘significant’ coefficient.

We check the residuals of the model to ensure that they are evenly distributed around 0:

plot(Rmodel0)

And check the qq plot:

qqnorm(residuals(Rmodel0))
qqline(residuals(Rmodel0), datax = FALSE, distribution = qnorm,
       probs = c(0.25, 0.75), qtype = 7, col="red")

Both look OK!

In most cases with a significant language effect, there is an increase in the relative length of /a:/. The exception to this is the historical female speakers, who seem to reduce the relative length of /a:/ while speaking te reo Māori. These results are discussed further in the paper.
